    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-07-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-07-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="675"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d675">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.3331/483: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Uruguay</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dawson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Montevideo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-07-21">July 21,
                            1942</date>.<lb/>[Received July 21—5:01 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>612. Trade Agreement was signed at Foreign Office at 5 p.m. today. Foreign Office
                    had arranged appropriate ceremony attended by considerable number of Uruguayan
                    officials, Embassy staff and American business men. Guani and I made brief
                    remarks both stressing importance of unconditional most favored nation clause as
                    means of assuring improved trade relations in better future world. Guani paid
                    tribute to our trade agreement policy.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dawson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <pb facs="0730" n="716" xml:id="pg_716"/>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[For text of trade agreement, see Department of State Executive Agreement
                        Series No. 276, or 56 Stat. (pt. 2) 1624; for analysis of agreement, see
                        Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, July 25, 1942,
                        supplement, page 654c.]</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
